RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: OK.

00:00:21.390 --> 00:00:26.650
Today, we're going to
talk about public policy.

00:00:26.650 --> 00:00:28.310
It'll be a little US-centric.

00:00:28.310 --> 00:00:30.430
We're going to walk
through Madison,

00:00:30.430 --> 00:00:32.650
talk about interest
group liberalism,

00:00:32.650 --> 00:00:34.900
other political
processes, and then

00:00:34.900 --> 00:00:39.040
begin the discussion of that
clean coal/dirty air trading

00:00:39.040 --> 00:00:42.160
filth case, with
mostly background

00:00:42.160 --> 00:00:44.240
and a couple of questions.

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:48.490
So I want to review from
way back in February.

00:00:48.490 --> 00:00:51.220
This is almost the
same slide, not quite.

00:00:51.220 --> 00:00:54.610
We talked about differences
between market processes

00:00:54.610 --> 00:00:57.190
and political processes.

00:00:57.190 --> 00:01:00.490
I will remind you
that governments

00:01:00.490 --> 00:01:04.420
tend to have, need to have,
a near monopoly of force.

00:01:04.420 --> 00:01:07.240
And if they're stable, they
tend to have legitimacy.

00:01:07.240 --> 00:01:12.040
That is to say there tends to be
a general acceptance that it's

00:01:12.040 --> 00:01:13.750
OK that they make
laws and rules,

00:01:13.750 --> 00:01:17.780
that the processes are OK,
that people are OK generally.

00:01:17.780 --> 00:01:20.530
Obviously, not everybody
agrees, and there

00:01:20.530 --> 00:01:24.460
are people in various
parts of this country who

00:01:24.460 --> 00:01:26.830
think the US government
should be overthrown.

00:01:26.830 --> 00:01:31.480
But by and large, Syria
is an interesting example.

00:01:31.480 --> 00:01:33.580
The government has a
near monopoly of force,

00:01:33.580 --> 00:01:36.490
clearly has very
little legitimacy.

00:01:36.490 --> 00:01:39.410
And whether it's a near monopoly
of force or not quite enough,

00:01:39.410 --> 00:01:40.540
we will see.

00:01:40.540 --> 00:01:42.880
We will see.

00:01:42.880 --> 00:01:46.690
Somalia, nobody has either.

00:01:46.690 --> 00:01:56.150
So the differences between
political processes and market

00:01:56.150 --> 00:01:57.980
processes-- in
market processes, we

00:01:57.980 --> 00:02:01.160
think about individuals
pursuing self-interest.

00:02:01.160 --> 00:02:04.070
In the political
sphere, individuals

00:02:04.070 --> 00:02:06.980
are actors and so are groups.

00:02:06.980 --> 00:02:10.430
And self-interest is not the
only thing that people pursue.

00:02:10.430 --> 00:02:14.660
They pursue their view of
what's good for everybody else.

00:02:14.660 --> 00:02:16.400
An awful lot of
government actions

00:02:16.400 --> 00:02:21.470
are what's good for you, not
just what's good for the actor.

00:02:21.470 --> 00:02:25.160
Collective choice-- choice made
for all of us, public goods,

00:02:25.160 --> 00:02:30.470
things that affect all of
us, and in market processes,

00:02:30.470 --> 00:02:32.870
we think about
individuals' preferences.

00:02:32.870 --> 00:02:34.970
What do I want?

00:02:34.970 --> 00:02:37.010
In political
processes, you really

00:02:37.010 --> 00:02:38.780
have to think about ideologies.

00:02:38.780 --> 00:02:42.740
Ideologies are views of the
proper function of society,

00:02:42.740 --> 00:02:47.000
the proper organization of
society, what's good for you

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:49.610
or what's good for all
of us, but certainly

00:02:49.610 --> 00:02:52.190
what's good for you.

00:02:52.190 --> 00:02:53.960
That doesn't arise
in the market.

00:02:53.960 --> 00:02:56.845
It does arise in
politics inevitably.

00:02:56.845 --> 00:02:58.220
When you're making
decisions that

00:02:58.220 --> 00:03:00.350
affect the whole
community, you have

00:03:00.350 --> 00:03:02.960
to have some notion of
what those decisions should

00:03:02.960 --> 00:03:05.730
look like, how they should
be made, and so forth.

00:03:05.730 --> 00:03:08.420
So ideology always matters.

00:03:08.420 --> 00:03:12.590
Market processes, we think
mostly about competition.

00:03:12.590 --> 00:03:15.320
But competition is
not the only process

00:03:15.320 --> 00:03:16.340
in the political sphere.

00:03:16.340 --> 00:03:18.620
Certainly as we
go into elections,

00:03:18.620 --> 00:03:20.750
we will think about influence.

00:03:20.750 --> 00:03:24.170
As you watch people
lining up behind Romney,

00:03:24.170 --> 00:03:27.410
you think about
cooperation as a key part

00:03:27.410 --> 00:03:29.090
of the political process.

00:03:29.090 --> 00:03:32.430
And as you see people
lining up behind Romney,

00:03:32.430 --> 00:03:35.870
who don't much like Romney, you
see the influence of loyalty.

00:03:35.870 --> 00:03:39.830
All those processes matter--
influence, cooperation,

00:03:39.830 --> 00:03:42.245
and loyalty matter in
the political sphere.

00:03:44.870 --> 00:03:47.930
In politics, power
is a goal for most

00:03:47.930 --> 00:03:53.060
of the actors, a goal
in and of itself--

00:03:53.060 --> 00:03:56.870
the ability to get other
people to act in my interest

00:03:56.870 --> 00:04:00.720
or in the public interest,
not in their interest.

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:03.320
And finally, I remind you
that there is no there

00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:05.850
is no perfect system.

00:04:05.850 --> 00:04:10.380
We talked briefly about
this voting paradox

00:04:10.380 --> 00:04:12.180
back in February--

00:04:12.180 --> 00:04:14.700
that it's quite possible.

00:04:14.700 --> 00:04:18.279
Just to remind you
what it looks like,

00:04:18.279 --> 00:04:22.770
we have three individuals,
individual one, two, and three.

00:04:22.770 --> 00:04:29.340
Three alternatives-- individual
one prefers A to B to C,

00:04:29.340 --> 00:04:32.310
individual two--

00:04:32.310 --> 00:04:36.240
let me be sure I
get this right--

00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:42.030
individual two
prefers C to A to B,

00:04:42.030 --> 00:04:56.620
and individual three prefers
B to C to A. So if we vote,

00:04:56.620 --> 00:05:02.650
two people prefer A
to B, so A beats B.

00:05:02.650 --> 00:05:08.320
Two people prefer
B to C, B beats C,

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:15.490
and two people prefer
C to A, So C beats A.

00:05:15.490 --> 00:05:19.030
So voting with those preferences
cannot produce consistent

00:05:19.030 --> 00:05:20.240
decisions.

00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:25.390
There's no sense in asking what
the optimal decision is here.

00:05:25.390 --> 00:05:29.110
If I can control the agenda, I
can determine the outcome, just

00:05:29.110 --> 00:05:31.390
the order of voting.

00:05:31.390 --> 00:05:42.860
If I want if I want A to win, I
will first vote B against C. B

00:05:42.860 --> 00:05:43.360
will win.

00:05:43.360 --> 00:05:45.850
I'll then vote A
against B. A will win.

00:05:45.850 --> 00:05:48.670
And you can see if you
can choose the order,

00:05:48.670 --> 00:05:50.690
you can choose the outcome.

00:05:50.690 --> 00:05:56.600
So the political system is more
complicated in many dimensions

00:05:56.600 --> 00:05:58.300
than the economic system.

00:05:58.300 --> 00:06:01.360
And this last point
basically says the notion

00:06:01.360 --> 00:06:05.350
that there is an optimal
design for government--

00:06:05.350 --> 00:06:08.550
this is something
basically Ken Arrow

00:06:08.550 --> 00:06:11.940
got a Nobel Prize for proving
in a very, very general way

00:06:11.940 --> 00:06:16.240
in 1950 in one of the shortest
doctoral dissertations

00:06:16.240 --> 00:06:18.180
in economics--

00:06:18.180 --> 00:06:20.970
the notion that there is an
optimal design for government

00:06:20.970 --> 00:06:22.480
is a dream.

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:24.320
There isn't.

00:06:24.320 --> 00:06:26.360
This says without a
dictator, you can't even

00:06:26.360 --> 00:06:28.740
get a consistent system.

00:06:28.740 --> 00:06:31.110
And that's a very
general result.

00:06:31.110 --> 00:06:34.790
So questions about any
of this before we go?

00:06:34.790 --> 00:06:36.710
We talked about all
of this stuff earlier.

00:06:36.710 --> 00:06:42.213
I'm just trying to get you in
a political frame of mind here.

00:06:42.213 --> 00:06:43.255
Then let's go to Madison.

00:06:46.730 --> 00:06:53.350
So Madison is writing
in the context

00:06:53.350 --> 00:06:56.210
of designing a government.

00:06:56.210 --> 00:06:58.420
It's easy to forget this.

00:06:58.420 --> 00:07:01.090
Having just read this very
long biography of Hamilton,

00:07:01.090 --> 00:07:03.760
I will do a little
history lesson.

00:07:08.180 --> 00:07:10.295
When the country started,
if you think about it,

00:07:10.295 --> 00:07:12.670
when they sat down to figure
out how the government ought

00:07:12.670 --> 00:07:16.570
to be organized, there
weren't any obvious models.

00:07:16.570 --> 00:07:19.240
There weren't any
republics of any size.

00:07:19.240 --> 00:07:22.690
Venice had sort of had one,
but there weren't any republics

00:07:22.690 --> 00:07:24.310
of any size currently.

00:07:24.310 --> 00:07:27.163
England had a king, and they
didn't want to do a king.

00:07:27.163 --> 00:07:29.080
So how do you run a
government without a king?

00:07:29.080 --> 00:07:32.530
Well, you could look back to
Rome, you could look to Athens.

00:07:32.530 --> 00:07:33.520
They lasted a while.

00:07:33.520 --> 00:07:35.020
They fell.

00:07:35.020 --> 00:07:39.640
The Roman Republic became
a dictatorship, basically,

00:07:39.640 --> 00:07:42.610
and Athens fell for
a variety of reasons,

00:07:42.610 --> 00:07:45.260
and really was a
democracy, which

00:07:45.260 --> 00:07:46.510
they didn't think they wanted.

00:07:46.510 --> 00:07:48.250
They wanted a republic.

00:07:48.250 --> 00:07:50.590
How would you do a republic?

00:07:50.590 --> 00:07:53.230
So it is quite
extraordinary if you read

00:07:53.230 --> 00:07:54.940
what they wrote at the time.

00:07:54.940 --> 00:07:59.340
It was, like, well, we can
look at what the Romans did.

00:07:59.340 --> 00:08:01.790
But if you look at the
details of the Roman setup,

00:08:01.790 --> 00:08:03.530
it was very strange.

00:08:03.530 --> 00:08:04.790
And you wouldn't want to--

00:08:04.790 --> 00:08:07.370
people held office for
a year and the nobility

00:08:07.370 --> 00:08:09.320
were the office holders.

00:08:09.320 --> 00:08:11.805
You wouldn't want to do that.

00:08:11.805 --> 00:08:12.680
So what would you do?

00:08:12.680 --> 00:08:14.660
The first thing they did
during the Revolution,

00:08:14.660 --> 00:08:16.490
they set up the Articles
of Confederation.

00:08:16.490 --> 00:08:19.910
And that really was
a deal between 13

00:08:19.910 --> 00:08:24.470
independent colonies,
each one a sovereign state

00:08:24.470 --> 00:08:26.180
in its own eyes.

00:08:26.180 --> 00:08:29.510
And the Articles
of Confederation

00:08:29.510 --> 00:08:31.070
didn't have any
executive branch.

00:08:31.070 --> 00:08:32.090
They had Congress.

00:08:32.090 --> 00:08:34.940
Didn't set up any
courts, and the Congress

00:08:34.940 --> 00:08:37.770
didn't have the
power to raise money.

00:08:37.770 --> 00:08:42.150
So the Congress had the
power to borrow money.

00:08:42.150 --> 00:08:47.150
And Congress could ask the
states to please send in money.

00:08:47.150 --> 00:08:48.550
And that had mixed results.

00:08:48.550 --> 00:08:50.330
So at the end of the
Revolution, there

00:08:50.330 --> 00:08:52.460
was a lot of national debt.

00:08:52.460 --> 00:08:55.520
We debt financed the
Revolution, because the states

00:08:55.520 --> 00:08:56.600
by and large--

00:08:56.600 --> 00:08:58.010
states also borrowed a lot.

00:08:58.010 --> 00:09:00.410
So there was a lot of
debt floating around,

00:09:00.410 --> 00:09:02.767
but you couldn't tax.

00:09:02.767 --> 00:09:04.850
We tried to run a government
that way for a while,

00:09:04.850 --> 00:09:07.980
but that didn't make any sense.

00:09:07.980 --> 00:09:10.670
So they sat down and they
drafted the Constitution.

00:09:10.670 --> 00:09:13.790
You will notice that's 10
years later, more or less.

00:09:13.790 --> 00:09:16.580
So they tried it for a
while during and after

00:09:16.580 --> 00:09:20.540
the Revolution, and then
they wrote the Constitution

00:09:20.540 --> 00:09:23.510
that we now have,
which everybody sort of

00:09:23.510 --> 00:09:25.550
treats as, yes, of course.

00:09:25.550 --> 00:09:27.500
That's what you would do.

00:09:27.500 --> 00:09:34.130
At the time it was
enormously controversial.

00:09:34.130 --> 00:09:37.220
It was not clear it
would be ratified.

00:09:37.220 --> 00:09:40.160
There was intense opposition,
particularly in New York,

00:09:40.160 --> 00:09:43.550
also in Virginia, the
two leading colonies,

00:09:43.550 --> 00:09:46.050
very organized opposition.

00:09:46.050 --> 00:09:48.260
The Governor of New
York opposed it.

00:09:48.260 --> 00:09:50.540
They did not want a
centralized power, which

00:09:50.540 --> 00:09:51.950
is what the Constitution did.

00:09:51.950 --> 00:09:54.170
It took power to the
central government.

00:09:54.170 --> 00:09:58.370
So we think of the
Federalist Papers

00:09:58.370 --> 00:10:06.500
as sort of reflections, idle
commentary, people with time

00:10:06.500 --> 00:10:08.570
on their hands talking
about what we intended

00:10:08.570 --> 00:10:10.130
when we wrote the Constitution.

00:10:10.130 --> 00:10:12.410
These were political documents.

00:10:12.410 --> 00:10:14.960
Madison was, all these
guys, were arguing here

00:10:14.960 --> 00:10:16.970
are reasons to ratify.

00:10:16.970 --> 00:10:19.530
Please ratify.

00:10:19.530 --> 00:10:24.480
So this was an explicitly
political document

00:10:24.480 --> 00:10:27.240
at a somewhat different level
than many political documents

00:10:27.240 --> 00:10:30.990
we see today, but it's
important to recognize

00:10:30.990 --> 00:10:32.310
this was in the heat of combat.

00:10:32.310 --> 00:10:34.470
This was something you
dash off over a weekend

00:10:34.470 --> 00:10:36.720
and then get to the next one.

00:10:36.720 --> 00:10:39.910
This was not written at
leisure in the study.

00:10:39.910 --> 00:10:43.600
So that's Madison.

00:10:43.600 --> 00:10:50.670
And what's the problem he's
addressing in Federalist 10?

00:10:53.770 --> 00:10:54.620
Max.

00:10:54.620 --> 00:10:55.420
AUDIENCE: Faction.

00:10:55.420 --> 00:10:57.574
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Faction, what's faction?

00:10:57.574 --> 00:11:00.418
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
people get together

00:11:00.418 --> 00:11:02.788
for a common goal [INAUDIBLE].

00:11:05.513 --> 00:11:07.680
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: So
it's not just a common goal,

00:11:07.680 --> 00:11:14.640
it's get what they want,
which is not a good thing.

00:11:14.640 --> 00:11:17.500
He defines "faction," as
you said, they get together.

00:11:17.500 --> 00:11:19.890
They're united and actuated
by a common impulse--

00:11:19.890 --> 00:11:21.680
I think that should
be "or passion."

00:11:21.680 --> 00:11:24.720
That's my typo, or
maybe it's "passion of."

00:11:24.720 --> 00:11:27.600
In any case, the key
is this last part--

00:11:27.600 --> 00:11:29.280
"adverse to the rights
of other citizens

00:11:29.280 --> 00:11:33.360
or the permanent and aggregate
interests of the community."

00:11:33.360 --> 00:11:38.850
At the end of the thing in one
of his illustrative remarks,

00:11:38.850 --> 00:11:43.380
he talks about a
"rage for paper money

00:11:43.380 --> 00:11:47.130
or for any other improper or
wicked project," dot, dot, dot.

00:11:47.130 --> 00:11:49.080
So that's the kind of
thing he has in mind,

00:11:49.080 --> 00:11:51.900
that a faction might actually
advocate what we carry around

00:11:51.900 --> 00:11:55.170
in our pockets every day,
which when he was writing

00:11:55.170 --> 00:11:57.000
was viewed as evil.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:11:58.860
Let's look at--
that's the problem.

00:11:58.860 --> 00:12:04.680
How, in a representative
republic or a democracy,

00:12:04.680 --> 00:12:09.220
where you want the will of
the people to drive decisions,

00:12:09.220 --> 00:12:11.760
how do you guard
against a set of people

00:12:11.760 --> 00:12:14.130
who want to do
things that basically

00:12:14.130 --> 00:12:18.510
trample on the rights of others
or would harm the community?

00:12:18.510 --> 00:12:19.610
How do you fix that?

00:12:19.610 --> 00:12:22.320
That's kind of an
interesting design problem.

00:12:22.320 --> 00:12:25.010
So let's walk through it.

00:12:25.010 --> 00:12:27.800
First, could you
eliminate factions?

00:12:27.800 --> 00:12:30.890
What do you say about that or
what do you think about that?

00:12:30.890 --> 00:12:33.830
Could you avoid
groups of people who

00:12:33.830 --> 00:12:36.350
want to do things that would
trample on the rights of others

00:12:36.350 --> 00:12:40.290
or be adverse to the long-term
interests of the community?

00:12:40.290 --> 00:12:41.250
Could you eliminate it?

00:12:44.227 --> 00:12:46.310
I can't call on you again,
because you've actually

00:12:46.310 --> 00:12:47.250
read the thing.

00:12:47.250 --> 00:12:48.080
I can tell.

00:12:48.080 --> 00:12:48.980
Anybody else?

00:12:48.980 --> 00:12:49.670
Kirsten.

00:12:49.670 --> 00:12:51.320
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
to eliminate the cause,

00:12:51.320 --> 00:12:53.445
you'd have to either
eliminate the people's liberty

00:12:53.445 --> 00:12:56.500
to choose or eliminate
their capability to think.

00:12:56.500 --> 00:12:59.160
That would be against--

00:12:59.160 --> 00:13:03.330
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Well,
apart from universal free beer,

00:13:03.330 --> 00:13:06.420
I'm not sure how you eliminate
their ability to think.

00:13:06.420 --> 00:13:09.270
He points in another
direction, though, doesn't he?

00:13:09.270 --> 00:13:15.350
He says, first you can
eliminate their liberty,

00:13:15.350 --> 00:13:19.440
but then suppose
they were all alike.

00:13:19.440 --> 00:13:21.320
Suppose everybody were the same.

00:13:21.320 --> 00:13:24.533
If you could do that, you
wouldn't have this problem.

00:13:24.533 --> 00:13:27.431
AUDIENCE: OK, not likely,
given that everybody

00:13:27.431 --> 00:13:30.329
can think for themselves,
and [INAUDIBLE]

00:13:30.329 --> 00:13:31.590
people reason through things.

00:13:31.590 --> 00:13:34.090
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: People
come with different conclusions.

00:13:34.090 --> 00:13:37.000
He also points to something
else that leads to differences.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:37.600
You're right.

00:13:37.600 --> 00:13:39.760
He says, you can't
eliminate liberty

00:13:39.760 --> 00:13:42.610
because that's the whole
point of the exercise.

00:13:42.610 --> 00:13:45.250
You can't eliminate
differences because people

00:13:45.250 --> 00:13:46.810
will have different opinions.

00:13:46.810 --> 00:13:49.090
He points to a
particular, and something

00:13:49.090 --> 00:13:52.120
we see these days, a
particularly important source

00:13:52.120 --> 00:13:53.170
of differences of view.

00:13:55.680 --> 00:13:56.337
Casey.

00:13:56.337 --> 00:13:57.420
AUDIENCE: Was it property?

00:13:57.420 --> 00:13:59.400
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
It was property, yeah.

00:13:59.400 --> 00:14:05.413
He says just the way life
goes, people accumulate.

00:14:05.413 --> 00:14:07.330
Some are rich, some are
poor, some have a lot,

00:14:07.330 --> 00:14:08.340
some have a little.

00:14:08.340 --> 00:14:10.332
That divides their interests.

00:14:10.332 --> 00:14:12.540
Rich people and poor people
have different interests.

00:14:12.540 --> 00:14:14.530
They're going to
have different views.

00:14:14.530 --> 00:14:17.520
So you can't keep
them from expressing

00:14:17.520 --> 00:14:18.930
their different views.

00:14:18.930 --> 00:14:20.430
That would be to
eliminate liberty.

00:14:20.430 --> 00:14:21.450
That would be unwise.

00:14:21.450 --> 00:14:23.310
And it would be
impractical, he says.

00:14:25.860 --> 00:14:27.510
Of course, the
Communist argument

00:14:27.510 --> 00:14:29.160
was, no, no, no, we should
eliminate differences

00:14:29.160 --> 00:14:29.660
in property.

00:14:29.660 --> 00:14:32.040
That will take care of it.

00:14:32.040 --> 00:14:33.720
He calls that
"impractical," which

00:14:33.720 --> 00:14:38.730
is pretty good diagnosis
in advance of Marx.

00:14:38.730 --> 00:14:41.310
So if you're going
to have factions,

00:14:41.310 --> 00:14:44.700
how do you deal with,
let's say, a small one?

00:14:44.700 --> 00:14:45.870
Is that a problem?

00:14:45.870 --> 00:14:47.620
Is that a problem you
have to worry about?

00:14:50.307 --> 00:14:52.640
We don't have tot have read
Madison to think about this.

00:14:52.640 --> 00:14:54.650
Suppose you're voting.

00:14:54.650 --> 00:14:56.420
Is a minority faction a problem?

00:14:59.390 --> 00:15:00.760
Say why.

00:15:00.760 --> 00:15:03.197
AUDIENCE: As long as they
accept the [INAUDIBLE] outcomes.

00:15:03.197 --> 00:15:04.780
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
As long as you're

00:15:04.780 --> 00:15:07.510
staying within the rules of the
game, a minority faction loses.

00:15:07.510 --> 00:15:09.080
They lose the vote.

00:15:09.080 --> 00:15:14.840
OK, that ought to
take care of that.

00:15:14.840 --> 00:15:21.015
Now he says, suppose you
have a pure democracy.

00:15:21.015 --> 00:15:22.390
You have a small
number of people

00:15:22.390 --> 00:15:25.420
gathered in a room,
or a small village,

00:15:25.420 --> 00:15:29.290
and it's one person, one vote.

00:15:29.290 --> 00:15:31.120
Can you ever
eliminate the problem

00:15:31.120 --> 00:15:33.430
of a majority faction,
which is clearly now

00:15:33.430 --> 00:15:35.210
the problem to deal with?

00:15:35.210 --> 00:15:36.790
You have the problem
of a majority

00:15:36.790 --> 00:15:40.870
that wants to trample
on the rights of others.

00:15:40.870 --> 00:15:44.410
Can you make that unlikely,
or rule it out, or rule out

00:15:44.410 --> 00:15:47.980
its effects when
you're small enough

00:15:47.980 --> 00:15:49.750
to have a pure democracy--

00:15:49.750 --> 00:15:52.030
no representation,
just everybody votes?

00:15:58.430 --> 00:16:00.050
Charlotte, you keep
waving your hand.

00:16:00.050 --> 00:16:02.930
I keep thinking you're raising,
but you're not raising it,

00:16:02.930 --> 00:16:03.570
are you?

00:16:03.570 --> 00:16:05.940
AUDIENCE: I mean, no, you
can't eliminate it [INAUDIBLE]

00:16:05.940 --> 00:16:06.440
democracy--

00:16:06.440 --> 00:16:06.805
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Exactly.

00:16:06.805 --> 00:16:07.580
AUDIENCE: Because
that's how it is,

00:16:07.580 --> 00:16:09.520
unless you change the
way they're thinking,

00:16:09.520 --> 00:16:11.228
which [INAUDIBLE] can't do.

00:16:11.228 --> 00:16:14.600
But if more people want it one
way, then they're going to win.

00:16:14.600 --> 00:16:16.350
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
They're going to win.

00:16:16.350 --> 00:16:18.980
And majority factions can happen
because you can do influence.

00:16:18.980 --> 00:16:20.520
You can do various other things.

00:16:20.520 --> 00:16:23.000
So his answer is, no, you can't.

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:26.780
So he says, OK, and then
he makes an argument

00:16:26.780 --> 00:16:29.510
that what you really
want is a large republic.

00:16:29.510 --> 00:16:33.920
That's the way to deal with the
problem of majority factions.

00:16:33.920 --> 00:16:36.140
Why?

00:16:36.140 --> 00:16:40.660
He gives two basic reasons,
one of which I think is wrong.

00:16:49.720 --> 00:16:50.230
Jessica.

00:16:50.230 --> 00:16:51.938
AUDIENCE: One of the
things is because he

00:16:51.938 --> 00:16:54.070
gives some sense of equal
power, so the bigger

00:16:54.070 --> 00:16:59.640
party that can decide where
that faction is going.

00:16:59.640 --> 00:17:01.920
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Well, I don't know

00:17:01.920 --> 00:17:03.300
what you mean by "equal power."

00:17:03.300 --> 00:17:07.020
He says if it's large,
there'll be diversity.

00:17:07.020 --> 00:17:09.750
But push that a little more.

00:17:09.750 --> 00:17:11.087
What do you mean by--

00:17:11.087 --> 00:17:13.670
AUDIENCE: A greater-- the
people ruling no matter

00:17:13.670 --> 00:17:16.790
how [INAUDIBLE] will be
able to somewhat-- it's

00:17:16.790 --> 00:17:18.730
sort of to the
[? knowledge ?] in a way,

00:17:18.730 --> 00:17:20.000
to have one of the final says.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:23.190
And then it's not
a pure democracy.

00:17:23.190 --> 00:17:27.180
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Well,
he has in mind a republic

00:17:27.180 --> 00:17:28.810
or a representative democracy.

00:17:28.810 --> 00:17:31.140
He has in mind a
situation where people

00:17:31.140 --> 00:17:33.480
are elected from
around the country,

00:17:33.480 --> 00:17:36.480
and those people are the
ultimate decision makers.

00:17:36.480 --> 00:17:41.340
So where they're elected,
you could imagine a majority

00:17:41.340 --> 00:17:43.080
faction, maybe.

00:17:43.080 --> 00:17:45.695
But Kirsten, you wanted to--

00:17:45.695 --> 00:17:47.070
AUDIENCE: You made
the assumption

00:17:47.070 --> 00:17:49.290
that elected officials
would represent

00:17:49.290 --> 00:17:53.610
the public good, [INAUDIBLE]
particularly necessary.

00:17:53.610 --> 00:17:54.697
And he--

00:17:54.697 --> 00:17:57.030
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: He kind
of hints at that direction,

00:17:57.030 --> 00:18:00.010
but he points someplace else.

00:18:00.010 --> 00:18:01.390
He does sort of say that.

00:18:01.390 --> 00:18:04.740
And then he does
say, at some point,

00:18:04.740 --> 00:18:07.030
that you can't count on it.

00:18:07.030 --> 00:18:12.420
He says, "It is vain to say
that enlightened statesmen will

00:18:12.420 --> 00:18:15.450
be able to adjust these
clashing interests.

00:18:15.450 --> 00:18:20.730
Enlightened statesmen will
not always be at the helm."

00:18:20.730 --> 00:18:25.590
So he points in that
direction and then backs off.

00:18:25.590 --> 00:18:28.710
Somebody else?

00:18:28.710 --> 00:18:31.590
Julian, what do you think?

00:18:31.590 --> 00:18:35.253
Forget Madison,
what might solve it?

00:18:35.253 --> 00:18:36.693
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:18:36.693 --> 00:18:38.610
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Yeah, but he's not there.

00:18:38.610 --> 00:18:39.235
He's not there.

00:18:39.235 --> 00:18:40.122
Yeah.

00:18:40.122 --> 00:18:41.580
AUDIENCE: You can
induce compromise

00:18:41.580 --> 00:18:45.660
by having representatives
be responsible for being

00:18:45.660 --> 00:18:48.780
accountable to lots of people
or by having enough people

00:18:48.780 --> 00:18:52.570
that, on any given issue, they
might fall into a faction,

00:18:52.570 --> 00:18:56.010
but you start compromising
because different sets of you

00:18:56.010 --> 00:18:58.710
will be in different
[INAUDIBLE] issues.

00:18:58.710 --> 00:19:00.720
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
That's a process issue,

00:19:00.720 --> 00:19:03.570
and maybe you can make
sure that kind of process

00:19:03.570 --> 00:19:05.880
is followed,
although if you look

00:19:05.880 --> 00:19:07.800
at how the Constitution
works in the US,

00:19:07.800 --> 00:19:10.530
you don't necessarily
see that happening.

00:19:10.530 --> 00:19:14.670
But he has in mind a
structural difference that--

00:19:18.390 --> 00:19:20.978
think back to what
the country looked

00:19:20.978 --> 00:19:22.020
like when he was writing.

00:19:25.950 --> 00:19:27.540
No electronic media.

00:19:27.540 --> 00:19:31.920
Weeks, months to
communicate north to south,

00:19:31.920 --> 00:19:37.020
east to west, lousy roads.

00:19:37.020 --> 00:19:39.750
Most rapid, most
efficient communication

00:19:39.750 --> 00:19:43.560
would be by sail, by the
ocean or on riverboats.

00:19:46.470 --> 00:19:48.930
Boston to Philadelphia
would be, say,

00:19:48.930 --> 00:19:50.610
to go to the
Constitutional Convention,

00:19:50.610 --> 00:19:54.390
would be measured not in hours
but in days, or maybe weeks,

00:19:54.390 --> 00:19:56.754
depending.

00:19:56.754 --> 00:19:59.880
You had very
different interests.

00:19:59.880 --> 00:20:02.760
You had people
trading on the coasts.

00:20:02.760 --> 00:20:05.190
You had people farming inland.

00:20:05.190 --> 00:20:09.840
You had heavily slave-dependent
societies in the South.

00:20:09.840 --> 00:20:13.630
You had some slavery in
the North, but not as much.

00:20:13.630 --> 00:20:20.040
And he basically argued that
that might be enough to do it.

00:20:20.040 --> 00:20:22.040
How could that work?

00:20:22.040 --> 00:20:23.790
That might be enough
to solve the problem.

00:20:23.790 --> 00:20:25.320
I mean, he doesn't
say that explicitly,

00:20:25.320 --> 00:20:27.112
but that's the world
in which he's writing.

00:20:30.840 --> 00:20:33.517
OK, Chad, you want
to take a shot?

00:20:33.517 --> 00:20:34.600
Don't want to take a shot.

00:20:34.600 --> 00:20:35.590
Andrew, you want to take a shot?

00:20:35.590 --> 00:20:36.430
Go ahead.

00:20:36.430 --> 00:20:40.850
AUDIENCE: OK, so I'm
just thinking this way

00:20:40.850 --> 00:20:42.730
and that's probably
confused [INAUDIBLE]..

00:20:42.730 --> 00:20:48.760
And I think it's if we
have bigger majority,

00:20:48.760 --> 00:20:51.590
it will be smaller
relative to the other one,

00:20:51.590 --> 00:20:54.853
meaning if the
republic is bigger,

00:20:54.853 --> 00:20:57.603
then the majority will not
be as big as [INAUDIBLE]..

00:20:57.603 --> 00:20:59.270
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
That's close to it.

00:20:59.270 --> 00:21:04.400
He argues if it's big, you're
likely to have local factions.

00:21:04.400 --> 00:21:05.450
That'll happen.

00:21:05.450 --> 00:21:10.430
You could have a majority of
the people in South Carolina

00:21:10.430 --> 00:21:12.905
want slavery forever
in the Constitution

00:21:12.905 --> 00:21:14.030
or not in the Constitution.

00:21:14.030 --> 00:21:18.710
They want some law
strongly favoring slavery,

00:21:18.710 --> 00:21:20.430
but that's South Carolina.

00:21:20.430 --> 00:21:23.900
And if there's
enough diversity, you

00:21:23.900 --> 00:21:27.190
could have local factions,
but not national factions.

00:21:27.190 --> 00:21:28.700
This is his basic argument.

00:21:28.700 --> 00:21:31.170
He has two arguments.

00:21:31.170 --> 00:21:36.020
One is he says if there are
larger districts, if you have

00:21:36.020 --> 00:21:38.270
a large republic,
then everybody's going

00:21:38.270 --> 00:21:40.310
to be elected by more people.

00:21:40.310 --> 00:21:43.380
And you'll probably get
better candidates that way.

00:21:43.380 --> 00:21:46.550
And he says, let me get this--

00:21:50.750 --> 00:21:52.880
"The proportion
of fit characters

00:21:52.880 --> 00:21:55.880
be not less in the large
than in the small republic,

00:21:55.880 --> 00:21:57.980
the former will present
a greater option

00:21:57.980 --> 00:22:01.430
and consequently, a greater
probability of a fit choice."

00:22:01.430 --> 00:22:03.290
And he says also, "As
each representative

00:22:03.290 --> 00:22:05.870
will be chosen by a greater
number of citizens in the large

00:22:05.870 --> 00:22:08.240
than in the small
republic, it will

00:22:08.240 --> 00:22:11.300
be more difficult for
unworthy candidates

00:22:11.300 --> 00:22:15.290
to practice, with success, the
vicious arts by which elections

00:22:15.290 --> 00:22:17.840
are too often carried."

00:22:17.840 --> 00:22:21.230
He was not thinking of
attack ads on television,

00:22:21.230 --> 00:22:24.230
however, which are more
easily done in large

00:22:24.230 --> 00:22:25.940
than in small districts.

00:22:25.940 --> 00:22:30.140
So I'm not persuaded by that.

00:22:30.140 --> 00:22:36.830
His second argument, though, is
the one we were inching toward,

00:22:36.830 --> 00:22:40.040
is extend the sphere.

00:22:40.040 --> 00:22:40.880
Make it larger.

00:22:40.880 --> 00:22:42.650
Make it more diverse.

00:22:42.650 --> 00:22:46.760
You make it less likely that a
majority of the whole country

00:22:46.760 --> 00:22:52.790
will coalesce around a
particular bad idea, a majority

00:22:52.790 --> 00:22:54.990
of the whole.

00:22:54.990 --> 00:22:58.190
Or if, in fact, a lot
of people think that,

00:22:58.190 --> 00:23:00.200
just because the place
is spread out-- again,

00:23:00.200 --> 00:23:03.080
no electronic communications--
the place is spread out.

00:23:03.080 --> 00:23:05.340
They won't be able
to find each other.

00:23:05.340 --> 00:23:07.670
It'll be harder for them to
discover their own strength

00:23:07.670 --> 00:23:09.140
and act in unison.

00:23:09.140 --> 00:23:13.670
So he argues we can deal
with this, basically,

00:23:13.670 --> 00:23:16.400
by you have a large republic.

00:23:16.400 --> 00:23:19.430
You have a lot of
parties and interests--

00:23:19.430 --> 00:23:23.600
and I'm going to spend time
on parties and interests.

00:23:23.600 --> 00:23:26.930
You make it less likely that
among all that diverse regional

00:23:26.930 --> 00:23:29.900
and industrial and
whatever interest,

00:23:29.900 --> 00:23:33.380
you will get a majority of
the whole country pointed

00:23:33.380 --> 00:23:35.600
in an unpleasant direction.

00:23:35.600 --> 00:23:39.590
You'll get competing,
diverse interests.

00:23:39.590 --> 00:23:43.070
He also is relying
on the fact that it

00:23:43.070 --> 00:23:47.630
will be hard to organize
if they're all spread out.

00:23:47.630 --> 00:23:49.130
I'm going to come
back to that, too.

00:23:49.130 --> 00:23:51.060
I don't think it's as
true now as it was then,

00:23:51.060 --> 00:23:53.900
but there's still truth to it.

00:23:53.900 --> 00:23:56.000
You see, this one I
think is a little odd.

00:23:59.910 --> 00:24:05.810
I once remember-- you've
never heard of Alan Simpson

00:24:05.810 --> 00:24:07.730
unless you really
follow politics closely

00:24:07.730 --> 00:24:09.980
and you've heard of the
Simpson-Bowles Deficit

00:24:09.980 --> 00:24:11.660
Reduction Panel.

00:24:11.660 --> 00:24:16.130
Alan Simpson was about 6 foot
5, one of the funniest men

00:24:16.130 --> 00:24:16.778
in Washington.

00:24:16.778 --> 00:24:19.070
And he was a Senator from
Wyoming, a Republican Senator

00:24:19.070 --> 00:24:23.960
from Wyoming, who had
a whole set of opinions

00:24:23.960 --> 00:24:26.180
on a whole set of issues
that were not particularly

00:24:26.180 --> 00:24:29.600
orthodox Republican positions.

00:24:29.600 --> 00:24:31.250
And I remember
somebody telling me

00:24:31.250 --> 00:24:33.830
that Wyoming's a small state.

00:24:33.830 --> 00:24:36.830
He can actually sit down and
explain himself to people.

00:24:36.830 --> 00:24:39.440
In California, you have to
communicate by television

00:24:39.440 --> 00:24:42.260
in 30-second spots.

00:24:42.260 --> 00:24:45.650
Simpson can go around and talk.

00:24:45.650 --> 00:24:50.450
So it's not clear to me you get
better candidates and better

00:24:50.450 --> 00:24:54.020
positions in large districts.

00:24:54.020 --> 00:24:58.820
But that's the solution.

00:24:58.820 --> 00:25:05.840
And in this solution, you get
a model of politics, sort of.

00:25:05.840 --> 00:25:08.330
The model of politics
is a great variety

00:25:08.330 --> 00:25:11.990
of parties and
interests competing,

00:25:11.990 --> 00:25:19.370
making it impossible or unlikely
that a big, single group will

00:25:19.370 --> 00:25:21.650
form and trample on the
rights of the minority,

00:25:21.650 --> 00:25:24.920
or be able to get
something stupid passed--

00:25:24.920 --> 00:25:28.660
something really stupid passed.

00:25:28.660 --> 00:25:31.210
Make some sense?

00:25:31.210 --> 00:25:32.192
Yeah.

00:25:32.192 --> 00:25:34.150
AUDIENCE: --argue that
the same process kind of

00:25:34.150 --> 00:25:37.213
makes it harder to get anything
passed, get anything done.

00:25:37.213 --> 00:25:39.130
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Well, the US Constitution

00:25:39.130 --> 00:25:44.170
is distinctive internationally
in how many obstacles

00:25:44.170 --> 00:25:46.960
it puts in front of
getting anything done.

00:25:46.960 --> 00:25:49.180
There was this great
fear of mob rule.

00:25:49.180 --> 00:25:51.160
There was this great fear.

00:25:51.160 --> 00:25:53.290
They'd had a king, so you
don't want the president

00:25:53.290 --> 00:25:54.740
to be too powerful.

00:25:54.740 --> 00:25:55.870
So you put a House.

00:25:55.870 --> 00:25:57.070
You put a Senate.

00:25:57.070 --> 00:26:00.760
And you're afraid that the House
may be governed by mob rule

00:26:00.760 --> 00:26:02.480
because it turns
over every two years.

00:26:02.480 --> 00:26:04.063
So you have the
Senate that's supposed

00:26:04.063 --> 00:26:07.870
to be deliberative, and more
aristocratic, and slower.

00:26:07.870 --> 00:26:11.530
And then, although they
hadn't really thought of it,

00:26:11.530 --> 00:26:12.850
they got it pretty quickly--

00:26:12.850 --> 00:26:15.400
you have the Supreme
Court that has the ability

00:26:15.400 --> 00:26:18.190
to say this violates
the Constitution.

00:26:18.190 --> 00:26:20.620
It isn't in the Constitution
that the Supreme Court can

00:26:20.620 --> 00:26:22.662
do that, but the Supreme
Court asserted it could,

00:26:22.662 --> 00:26:25.430
and it did, and has.

00:26:25.430 --> 00:26:28.330
So the US system--

00:26:28.330 --> 00:26:30.835
it's actually hard to explain
to people outside the US

00:26:30.835 --> 00:26:32.710
that we do not have a
government in the sense

00:26:32.710 --> 00:26:34.150
that they have a government.

00:26:34.150 --> 00:26:38.320
In a parliamentary
system, the coalition that

00:26:38.320 --> 00:26:43.180
controls parliament
names the prime minister.

00:26:43.180 --> 00:26:47.080
If the government of which
the prime minister is the head

00:26:47.080 --> 00:26:49.810
introduces a major law
or introduces a budget

00:26:49.810 --> 00:26:51.560
and it doesn't pass,
the government falls.

00:26:51.560 --> 00:26:53.320
You have another election.

00:26:53.320 --> 00:26:55.360
So when the prime
minister says we're

00:26:55.360 --> 00:26:59.500
going to ratify this treaty,
he either ratifies the treaty

00:26:59.500 --> 00:27:02.170
or he's gone.

00:27:02.170 --> 00:27:03.460
We have nothing like that.

00:27:03.460 --> 00:27:06.910
We don't have a government
that can make promises.

00:27:06.910 --> 00:27:08.223
Most countries do.

00:27:08.223 --> 00:27:08.890
So you're right.

00:27:08.890 --> 00:27:12.790
We set it up so we
don't have a king.

00:27:12.790 --> 00:27:15.640
We don't have the House of
Representatives in charge.

00:27:15.640 --> 00:27:18.580
To a first approximation, we
don't have anybody in charge.

00:27:18.580 --> 00:27:23.770
Now, in the 18th century, this
was considered a good thing.

00:27:23.770 --> 00:27:25.870
It still has its merits.

00:27:25.870 --> 00:27:31.720
It means it's hard
to act in haste.

00:27:31.720 --> 00:27:34.180
One of the critiques of
parliamentary systems

00:27:34.180 --> 00:27:36.610
is they can go from a
set of left-wing policies

00:27:36.610 --> 00:27:39.910
to a set of right-wing
policies with one election.

00:27:39.910 --> 00:27:44.410
We move more slowly,
for better or for worse.

00:27:44.410 --> 00:27:46.840
But you're right--
the whole Constitution

00:27:46.840 --> 00:27:51.800
is designed to prevent action
to a first approximation.

00:27:51.800 --> 00:27:59.510
OK, Madison's model, then,
is one of competing interest

00:27:59.510 --> 00:28:00.010
groups.

00:28:04.230 --> 00:28:07.530
Factions are inevitable,
but if they're weak,

00:28:07.530 --> 00:28:10.530
if they're small and
weak, they don't dominate.

00:28:10.530 --> 00:28:14.310
And it's interesting--
if you go from Madison,

00:28:14.310 --> 00:28:18.210
and I must say I'm sure you all
find [? Loewy ?] easy to read.

00:28:18.210 --> 00:28:19.740
I find him almost
incomprehensible,

00:28:19.740 --> 00:28:24.530
but this is a standard text.

00:28:24.530 --> 00:28:28.380
He argues-- this is written
in the '60s, but I think

00:28:28.380 --> 00:28:31.290
it's still implicitly true--

00:28:31.290 --> 00:28:34.230
that competition
among interest groups

00:28:34.230 --> 00:28:40.400
has been both an accepted
description of US politics,

00:28:40.400 --> 00:28:42.440
and politics in
some other settings,

00:28:42.440 --> 00:28:45.410
and implicitly, an ideal.

00:28:45.410 --> 00:28:48.800
If you go to Washington
and look in the phone book,

00:28:48.800 --> 00:28:53.600
look in buildings on K
Street, you will see--

00:28:53.600 --> 00:28:56.300
I spoke yesterday
to an interest group

00:28:56.300 --> 00:29:01.260
composed of large industrial
users of electricity.

00:29:01.260 --> 00:29:06.320
I was preceded by a spokesperson
for the American Public Power

00:29:06.320 --> 00:29:11.000
Association, which represents
municipal and cooperative power

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:11.720
consumers.

00:29:14.420 --> 00:29:17.540
We were sharing quarters with
the American Forest Products

00:29:17.540 --> 00:29:22.580
Association, which
represents timber harvesters.

00:29:22.580 --> 00:29:25.850
You can go up and
down the street

00:29:25.850 --> 00:29:28.130
and there's the
Department of Agriculture,

00:29:28.130 --> 00:29:31.430
set up as an interest
group, basically,

00:29:31.430 --> 00:29:34.740
to represent the farm
community, and on, and on.

00:29:34.740 --> 00:29:38.485
So the argument [? Loewy ?]
makes is that we've moved.

00:29:38.485 --> 00:29:39.860
And I think though
he was writing

00:29:39.860 --> 00:29:41.780
in the '60s that isn't bad.

00:29:41.780 --> 00:29:46.550
That has become both an
accepted description.

00:29:46.550 --> 00:29:48.290
Think about how
politics are described

00:29:48.290 --> 00:29:52.040
in the press, not presidential
politics, but any kind

00:29:52.040 --> 00:29:53.840
of legislative decision.

00:29:53.840 --> 00:29:57.530
The environmental community,
the Black community, women--

00:29:57.530 --> 00:30:02.450
we describe the political
process in terms of groups,

00:30:02.450 --> 00:30:04.470
often--

00:30:04.470 --> 00:30:07.270
the Cuban community in
Atlanta, blah, blah, blah.

00:30:07.270 --> 00:30:09.540
I mean, we do a lot
of group description.

00:30:09.540 --> 00:30:16.050
And it's almost--
here's the next step--

00:30:16.050 --> 00:30:17.460
it's viewed as a good thing.

00:30:20.050 --> 00:30:23.730
And the question is,
is it a good thing?

00:30:23.730 --> 00:30:26.700
First of all, is it an accurate
description of politics?

00:30:26.700 --> 00:30:31.380
And I'll come back to that--
sometimes yes, sometimes no.

00:30:31.380 --> 00:30:36.240
But first, [? Loewy ?] has
a nice, little statement

00:30:36.240 --> 00:30:43.340
about if politics looked like
that, could it be a good thing?

00:30:43.340 --> 00:30:47.780
And he argues you'd sort
of need three pieces.

00:30:47.780 --> 00:30:53.390
First, you'd need
clearly defined groups.

00:30:53.390 --> 00:30:56.450
Large consumers of electricity
is a pretty clearly defined

00:30:56.450 --> 00:30:58.580
group, but you can see it blurs.

00:30:58.580 --> 00:31:02.570
But certainly cooperative
and municipal utilities

00:31:02.570 --> 00:31:05.730
that buy electricity--
that's a well-defined group.

00:31:05.730 --> 00:31:08.120
The Forest Products
Association probably is.

00:31:11.010 --> 00:31:13.010
And then there's this--

00:31:13.010 --> 00:31:15.050
I think of it mathematically
as [? spanning-- ?]

00:31:15.050 --> 00:31:21.350
the notion is that the
organized groups pretty much

00:31:21.350 --> 00:31:23.480
cover the universe.

00:31:23.480 --> 00:31:25.460
Pretty much every
interest that matters

00:31:25.460 --> 00:31:30.110
is represented well
by an organized group,

00:31:30.110 --> 00:31:31.430
so that everybody's covered.

00:31:31.430 --> 00:31:35.610
Everybody has a group, or not
everybody, every interest.

00:31:35.610 --> 00:31:37.790
So you may be represented
by several groups,

00:31:37.790 --> 00:31:40.970
depending on what you're
thinking about at the moment.

00:31:40.970 --> 00:31:44.750
And then if you believe that
as a statement of ideology,

00:31:44.750 --> 00:31:47.793
as a statement about how
the world should work,

00:31:47.793 --> 00:31:49.460
that the role of
government is basically

00:31:49.460 --> 00:31:54.510
to balance and reconcile, to
do deals among various groups.

00:31:54.510 --> 00:31:58.130
You ensure access so all
groups can participate.

00:31:58.130 --> 00:32:00.290
And this is his language--

00:32:00.290 --> 00:32:02.930
"You ratify the
agreements and adjustments

00:32:02.930 --> 00:32:05.600
worked out among them."

00:32:05.600 --> 00:32:09.440
So again, you hear
legislative deals in Congress.

00:32:09.440 --> 00:32:14.810
And we'll talk about
at length the time

00:32:14.810 --> 00:32:19.820
after next in this case where
people explicitly say, look,

00:32:19.820 --> 00:32:21.290
these guys won in Congress.

00:32:21.290 --> 00:32:23.450
And so our job is to
make sure they get it.

00:32:23.450 --> 00:32:25.580
They get the fruits
of their victory.

00:32:25.580 --> 00:32:32.310
So do those makes sense as
descriptions of the world

00:32:32.310 --> 00:32:33.450
as you know it?

00:32:33.450 --> 00:32:36.540
Does that make sense as a
description of a good world?

00:32:41.160 --> 00:32:43.080
Catherine.

00:32:43.080 --> 00:32:52.200
AUDIENCE: So I agree that
having organized [INAUDIBLE]

00:32:52.200 --> 00:32:54.963
but the problem that he talked
about business interests,

00:32:54.963 --> 00:32:56.380
like generally the
interest group,

00:32:56.380 --> 00:33:00.772
but there was money [INAUDIBLE]
given that Representatives

00:33:00.772 --> 00:33:05.140
in the Senate and House,
they want to get re-elected.

00:33:05.140 --> 00:33:08.770
And so the group that
has the most money

00:33:08.770 --> 00:33:11.257
can have a larger [INAUDIBLE].

00:33:11.257 --> 00:33:13.840
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: So you're
pointing-- and I think I would,

00:33:13.840 --> 00:33:14.470
too--

00:33:14.470 --> 00:33:23.020
you're pointing sort of to the
second of those assumptions,

00:33:23.020 --> 00:33:26.350
particularly the "adequately
represent" part of it.

00:33:26.350 --> 00:33:31.930
So what you're saying is not
all groups are created equal.

00:33:31.930 --> 00:33:33.370
I think that's fair.

00:33:33.370 --> 00:33:35.680
Are all possible
interests represented

00:33:35.680 --> 00:33:38.770
by organized groups?

00:33:38.770 --> 00:33:45.130
AUDIENCE: No, but I think
that a group has a view,

00:33:45.130 --> 00:33:50.100
and if New York was [INAUDIBLE]
large enough to influence,

00:33:50.100 --> 00:33:51.866
then I think [INAUDIBLE].

00:33:54.528 --> 00:33:56.570
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Who
represents the interests

00:33:56.570 --> 00:34:00.380
of mobile phone users?

00:34:00.380 --> 00:34:03.830
Is there an organized group?

00:34:03.830 --> 00:34:08.150
Or buyers of milk--

00:34:08.150 --> 00:34:10.040
we have a federal
milk price support

00:34:10.040 --> 00:34:14.159
program that's designed to
raise the price of whole milk.

00:34:14.159 --> 00:34:18.250
The dairy farmers are an
effectively organized group.

00:34:18.250 --> 00:34:22.320
People who give milk to
their kids, not so much.

00:34:22.320 --> 00:34:23.810
So I would point to both parts.

00:34:23.810 --> 00:34:24.659
I agree with you.

00:34:24.659 --> 00:34:26.360
I agree with you on the second--

00:34:26.360 --> 00:34:28.770
not all groups
are created equal,

00:34:28.770 --> 00:34:33.889
so you don't necessarily get the
kind of balance you might like.

00:34:33.889 --> 00:34:37.730
But I'm not sure
they fill up most

00:34:37.730 --> 00:34:40.730
of the sectors of our lives.

00:34:40.730 --> 00:34:46.070
And what's
interesting-- yesterday

00:34:46.070 --> 00:34:48.050
was a good day for anecdotes.

00:34:48.050 --> 00:34:52.520
So the speaker from the
Public Power Association

00:34:52.520 --> 00:34:55.520
said she was very
happy to be addressing

00:34:55.520 --> 00:34:59.810
these large industrial
consumers because, she said,

00:34:59.810 --> 00:35:02.540
your group and my group
are the only ones that

00:35:02.540 --> 00:35:07.710
represent consumers of
electricity, which probably

00:35:07.710 --> 00:35:08.580
makes sense.

00:35:08.580 --> 00:35:13.290
Small businesses aren't
represented in Washington

00:35:13.290 --> 00:35:16.410
as consumers of electricity.

00:35:16.410 --> 00:35:19.240
There is a National Federation
of independent Businesses,

00:35:19.240 --> 00:35:22.210
but it's got a lot of issues.

00:35:22.210 --> 00:35:25.570
Nobody's representing me as
a consumer of electricity,

00:35:25.570 --> 00:35:28.150
as far as I can tell.

00:35:28.150 --> 00:35:33.310
So when we were talking
particularly about the FERC,

00:35:33.310 --> 00:35:36.970
when there is a proceeding,
a regulatory proceeding

00:35:36.970 --> 00:35:39.590
at the FERC, a notice goes out.

00:35:39.590 --> 00:35:40.430
You don't see it.

00:35:40.430 --> 00:35:41.750
I don't see it.

00:35:41.750 --> 00:35:42.350
They see it.

00:35:42.350 --> 00:35:43.070
That's their job.

00:35:43.070 --> 00:35:44.270
They're in Washington.

00:35:44.270 --> 00:35:46.040
And they respond to it.

00:35:46.040 --> 00:35:50.480
And with some luck, they respond
as consumers of electricity,

00:35:50.480 --> 00:35:51.980
but they're consumers
of electricity

00:35:51.980 --> 00:35:55.520
with particular interests.

00:35:55.520 --> 00:35:58.840
They don't necessarily
represent me.

00:35:58.840 --> 00:36:01.172
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:36:01.172 --> 00:36:02.630
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Yeah, but look

00:36:02.630 --> 00:36:04.560
at all the residential
users of electricity.

00:36:04.560 --> 00:36:07.160
That's a lot of volume.

00:36:07.160 --> 00:36:11.090
Hard to organize,
though, hard to organize.

00:36:11.090 --> 00:36:14.090
So that's one kicker.

00:36:14.090 --> 00:36:15.170
Anybody else?

00:36:15.170 --> 00:36:16.770
I picked on Catherine enough.

00:36:16.770 --> 00:36:17.270
Charlotte.

00:36:17.270 --> 00:36:19.263
AUDIENCE: I just had a question.

00:36:19.263 --> 00:36:21.680
So one of the things you were
listing earlier about things

00:36:21.680 --> 00:36:23.263
that Madison was
considering factions,

00:36:23.263 --> 00:36:24.890
like slavery or
trade, those are all

00:36:24.890 --> 00:36:27.560
things that I think of as having
to go with a political party,

00:36:27.560 --> 00:36:29.270
whereas the things you're
talking about now as factions

00:36:29.270 --> 00:36:30.590
are things that I wouldn't
think about having

00:36:30.590 --> 00:36:31.798
to do with a political party.

00:36:31.798 --> 00:36:34.760
So I guess how is
Madison relating factions

00:36:34.760 --> 00:36:37.183
to political parties or
what was the situation then?

00:36:37.183 --> 00:36:38.600
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
They actually

00:36:38.600 --> 00:36:41.540
hoped, a number
of them early on,

00:36:41.540 --> 00:36:44.387
that you wouldn't have parties,
which was really pretty--

00:36:44.387 --> 00:36:45.220
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:36:45.220 --> 00:36:46.440
AUDIENCE: There'd been
a loyalist person that

00:36:46.440 --> 00:36:48.868
[? hadn't ?] developed
another one yet [INAUDIBLE]..

00:36:48.868 --> 00:36:50.660
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
No, I mean, Washington

00:36:50.660 --> 00:36:52.910
had sufficient
charisma that until you

00:36:52.910 --> 00:36:57.440
began to coalesce opposition to
Washington, and in particular

00:36:57.440 --> 00:36:58.940
to Hamilton--

00:36:58.940 --> 00:37:01.890
Hamilton had a particular agenda
for the central government,

00:37:01.890 --> 00:37:03.620
which is to strengthen it.

00:37:03.620 --> 00:37:09.230
And Jefferson, and soon
Madison, opposed that strongly.

00:37:09.230 --> 00:37:11.616
But--

00:37:11.616 --> 00:37:16.610
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] also
some sort faction [INAUDIBLE]??

00:37:16.610 --> 00:37:20.720
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
It's interesting.

00:37:20.720 --> 00:37:24.420
And that was a fear,
that if you manage

00:37:24.420 --> 00:37:28.370
to get a large
parity as faction,

00:37:28.370 --> 00:37:31.618
you could have exactly
the problem that Madison

00:37:31.618 --> 00:37:34.160
thought of, which is one reason
why they didn't like parties.

00:37:37.160 --> 00:37:43.580
Traditionally, American
political parties

00:37:43.580 --> 00:37:46.010
have been pretty big tents.

00:37:46.010 --> 00:37:50.210
They've represented a lot
of different interests

00:37:50.210 --> 00:37:52.940
that didn't see eye
to eye on all issues.

00:37:52.940 --> 00:37:56.520
In the European tradition,
parties tended to be narrower.

00:37:56.520 --> 00:37:59.400
So you'll have the
Labor Party in Britain,

00:37:59.400 --> 00:38:01.820
which is was a left
party, but traditionally

00:38:01.820 --> 00:38:05.150
really was aligned with
the labor movement,

00:38:05.150 --> 00:38:08.660
as the Democratic
Party was and is,

00:38:08.660 --> 00:38:12.500
but much more tightly
than the Democratic Party.

00:38:12.500 --> 00:38:14.630
So I think it depends on
the nature of the party.

00:38:14.630 --> 00:38:16.670
And in some
parliamentary systems,

00:38:16.670 --> 00:38:19.040
you have very little
parties that are

00:38:19.040 --> 00:38:21.140
focused on particular issues.

00:38:21.140 --> 00:38:23.780
Think about the ultra-orthodox
parties in Israel,

00:38:23.780 --> 00:38:27.290
for instance, or some
of the far left parties

00:38:27.290 --> 00:38:30.380
in European politics.

00:38:30.380 --> 00:38:33.410
Our parties have traditionally
not been easily identified

00:38:33.410 --> 00:38:35.180
with particular factions.

00:38:35.180 --> 00:38:37.790
And there isn't a--

00:38:37.790 --> 00:38:39.260
well, I'm going to
talk about this,

00:38:39.260 --> 00:38:44.120
but most of the interest groups
we see in the US try very hard

00:38:44.120 --> 00:38:46.700
not to be identified with
one party or another.

00:38:46.700 --> 00:38:49.108
Because you don't want
to-- if you could possibly

00:38:49.108 --> 00:38:50.900
be friends with everybody,
you can survive.

00:38:53.690 --> 00:38:59.660
Pro-choice, pro-life, they have
not been able to do that trick.

00:38:59.660 --> 00:39:02.270
There's a Republican side
and a Democratic side,

00:39:02.270 --> 00:39:03.890
and there they are.

00:39:03.890 --> 00:39:09.020
But most-- the Forest Products
Association, I am sure,

00:39:09.020 --> 00:39:12.200
contributes to people
from both parties.

00:39:12.200 --> 00:39:14.540
The large consumers of
electricity, I'm sure,

00:39:14.540 --> 00:39:17.260
contribute to people,
et cetera, et cetera.

00:39:17.260 --> 00:39:18.920
So good question, though.

00:39:18.920 --> 00:39:21.230
Anything else?

00:39:21.230 --> 00:39:30.110
OK, so I guess I'm
inclined to agree with,

00:39:30.110 --> 00:39:35.780
I think with Catherine,
that this probably doesn't

00:39:35.780 --> 00:39:38.603
work as well as one might like.

00:39:38.603 --> 00:39:40.520
I don't know whether
it's an ideal, whether it

00:39:40.520 --> 00:39:42.770
would work as an ideal or not.

00:39:42.770 --> 00:39:44.600
It's not a bad story.

00:39:44.600 --> 00:39:48.890
But the notion that pretty much
all interests are represented

00:39:48.890 --> 00:39:54.560
and they're well represented,
and that government is about--

00:39:54.560 --> 00:40:00.050
modulo the role of parties--
is about refereeing agreements

00:40:00.050 --> 00:40:01.670
and adjustments among
interest groups,

00:40:01.670 --> 00:40:04.790
is not a bad
description sometimes--

00:40:04.790 --> 00:40:07.540
sometimes.

00:40:07.540 --> 00:40:09.820
Once again, sometimes.

00:40:09.820 --> 00:40:12.580
But I'm not sure it's an ideal.

00:40:12.580 --> 00:40:16.990
OK, let me move on.

00:40:16.990 --> 00:40:19.870
A little bit about interest
group competition--

00:40:19.870 --> 00:40:26.720
first, if you think
about interest groups,

00:40:26.720 --> 00:40:31.730
their ability to
organize is really key.

00:40:31.730 --> 00:40:33.620
Those large consumers
of electricity--

00:40:33.620 --> 00:40:35.792
there are about 40 of them--

00:40:35.792 --> 00:40:37.640
they're the big
industrial buyers.

00:40:37.640 --> 00:40:40.280
They sit in a room.

00:40:40.280 --> 00:40:43.555
Small consumers of electricity--
there are many of us.

00:40:43.555 --> 00:40:44.930
We also have
different interests.

00:40:44.930 --> 00:40:46.638
We're in different
parts of the country--

00:40:46.638 --> 00:40:48.350
hard to organize.

00:40:48.350 --> 00:40:53.120
The more important an issue is--

00:40:53.120 --> 00:40:56.323
that should be higher
dollar "stake," not "stage."

00:40:56.323 --> 00:40:58.490
I'm looking at that and
saying that makes no sense--

00:40:58.490 --> 00:40:58.990
"stake."

00:41:02.060 --> 00:41:05.240
Electricity is 2% of the
average family budget.

00:41:05.240 --> 00:41:06.950
You're not going to
get families to rally

00:41:06.950 --> 00:41:08.930
around electricity rate reform.

00:41:08.930 --> 00:41:10.610
It's just not important enough.

00:41:10.610 --> 00:41:13.040
It's a big deal to the big guys.

00:41:13.040 --> 00:41:15.380
They'll send people
to Washington.

00:41:15.380 --> 00:41:18.710
And there are a small number
of them, so they organize.

00:41:18.710 --> 00:41:26.060
So a classic example is debates
about airline deregulation

00:41:26.060 --> 00:41:26.970
back in the '70s.

00:41:26.970 --> 00:41:29.000
The airlines were
well organized,

00:41:29.000 --> 00:41:31.700
were very important in Congress.

00:41:31.700 --> 00:41:33.560
Most did not want
to be deregulated,

00:41:33.560 --> 00:41:36.260
thank you very much.

00:41:36.260 --> 00:41:39.050
Travelers did not have
an interest group.

00:41:39.050 --> 00:41:41.210
There is an Airline
Passengers Association.

00:41:41.210 --> 00:41:42.920
I have no idea
who belongs to it,

00:41:42.920 --> 00:41:46.820
but not a particularly
important group.

00:41:46.820 --> 00:41:48.860
Nonetheless, they
were deregulated,

00:41:48.860 --> 00:41:50.510
something we may come back to.

00:41:50.510 --> 00:41:55.580
But the shorthand in politics
is a concentrated interest,

00:41:55.580 --> 00:41:58.010
an interest that affects
a small number of people

00:41:58.010 --> 00:42:00.290
and has a big
stake for each one,

00:42:00.290 --> 00:42:02.580
tends to be a potent interest.

00:42:02.580 --> 00:42:06.080
So back to are all interest
groups created equal?

00:42:06.080 --> 00:42:07.640
Well, no.

00:42:07.640 --> 00:42:09.950
Some groups don't organize.

00:42:09.950 --> 00:42:13.280
Back to regulating
electric utilities--

00:42:13.280 --> 00:42:15.980
the utility cares
an enormous amount

00:42:15.980 --> 00:42:18.060
about the outcome of regulation.

00:42:18.060 --> 00:42:20.570
Those of us who buy
care a little bit.

00:42:20.570 --> 00:42:22.550
There are a lot of us.

00:42:22.550 --> 00:42:25.100
We don't have that
much influence,

00:42:25.100 --> 00:42:26.630
except from time to time.

00:42:26.630 --> 00:42:31.130
So a key factor is how easy
is it to organize in terms

00:42:31.130 --> 00:42:35.120
of interest group competition.

00:42:35.120 --> 00:42:44.430
Money-- money is interesting.

00:42:44.430 --> 00:42:48.690
The simple assumption
is that you buy votes

00:42:48.690 --> 00:42:52.740
with campaign contributions,
and some of that does happen.

00:42:52.740 --> 00:42:56.130
But if you look at the
pattern of spending,

00:42:56.130 --> 00:43:00.353
people contribute to
politicians of both sides.

00:43:00.353 --> 00:43:02.520
If you become chairman of
a congressional committee,

00:43:02.520 --> 00:43:04.590
you will get campaign
contributions

00:43:04.590 --> 00:43:08.742
from anybody your
committee touches.

00:43:08.742 --> 00:43:10.950
Usually, what you want to
do is you want to make sure

00:43:10.950 --> 00:43:13.300
your friends win.

00:43:13.300 --> 00:43:18.940
It's harder to make somebody
make a 180-degree turn, or even

00:43:18.940 --> 00:43:21.190
a 90-degree turn
on an issue than it

00:43:21.190 --> 00:43:24.730
is to elect somebody who
already agrees with you.

00:43:24.730 --> 00:43:27.940
So an awful lot of what
goes on is electing friends

00:43:27.940 --> 00:43:31.320
and getting access.

00:43:31.320 --> 00:43:33.820
Getting access-- if you've given
a lot of money to somebody,

00:43:33.820 --> 00:43:36.100
they will return
your phone call.

00:43:36.100 --> 00:43:40.450
But it's amazing--
people who have

00:43:40.450 --> 00:43:44.350
no challenge, no
effective opposition,

00:43:44.350 --> 00:43:48.130
will get campaign contributions
from people who disagree

00:43:48.130 --> 00:43:50.380
with them on issues,
just because I want

00:43:50.380 --> 00:43:52.990
to be able to get in the door.

00:43:52.990 --> 00:43:54.880
I want you to think well of me.

00:43:54.880 --> 00:43:57.340
If I think you can be beaten
by somebody who I like better,

00:43:57.340 --> 00:43:59.890
I will pay a lot for them.

00:43:59.890 --> 00:44:02.830
But it's pretty
hard to buy votes

00:44:02.830 --> 00:44:04.330
with campaign contributions.

00:44:04.330 --> 00:44:08.270
The other thing-- and this
all merits discussion--

00:44:08.270 --> 00:44:10.120
the other thing that
has to be mentioned

00:44:10.120 --> 00:44:14.290
is the Citizens United decision,
which is this recent Supreme

00:44:14.290 --> 00:44:16.030
Court decision that
said corporations

00:44:16.030 --> 00:44:20.280
are people and limits on
spending are limits on speech.

00:44:20.280 --> 00:44:24.000
So you saw it in the primary.

00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:26.670
You didn't see it
here particularly,

00:44:26.670 --> 00:44:29.070
but other people saw it.

00:44:29.070 --> 00:44:30.690
There's really no
limit on what can

00:44:30.690 --> 00:44:37.750
be spent to support a candidate
by wealthy individuals,

00:44:37.750 --> 00:44:39.070
mainly, more than corporations.

00:44:39.070 --> 00:44:43.360
We talked about corporate
political action.

00:44:43.360 --> 00:44:47.620
But that may change
things dramatically.

00:44:47.620 --> 00:44:52.330
And it goes back to
Catherine's point about money.

00:44:52.330 --> 00:44:55.210
If you're free to
speak with your $5,

00:44:55.210 --> 00:44:57.670
and I'm free to speak
with my $50 million,

00:44:57.670 --> 00:45:01.150
we have different impact.

00:45:01.150 --> 00:45:05.350
So can I get my friends elected?

00:45:05.350 --> 00:45:07.990
Well, yeah, probably.

00:45:07.990 --> 00:45:09.550
Can I buy votes with it?

00:45:09.550 --> 00:45:10.540
Buying votes is hard.

00:45:10.540 --> 00:45:13.850
Getting friends
elected is easier.

00:45:13.850 --> 00:45:17.980
So we're going to
see more of that.

00:45:17.980 --> 00:45:20.800
We're going to see a lot of--

00:45:20.800 --> 00:45:22.420
this will be a very ugly Fall.

00:45:22.420 --> 00:45:23.920
That's all I have to say.

00:45:23.920 --> 00:45:28.060
Comments on any of this before
I go to the last one, last point

00:45:28.060 --> 00:45:28.600
here?

00:45:28.600 --> 00:45:29.620
Reactions, thoughts?

00:45:32.600 --> 00:45:34.370
Jacob, you look disturbed.

00:45:34.370 --> 00:45:35.250
David is disturbed.

00:45:35.250 --> 00:45:35.750
David.

