00:46:07.287 --> 00:46:09.370
AUDIENCE: Rich people are
individuals, too, right?

00:46:09.370 --> 00:46:12.100
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Yes, yes, yes, yes.

00:46:12.100 --> 00:46:17.710
Which are you imagining yourself
to be, you or a Warren Buffett?

00:46:17.710 --> 00:46:20.240
Because the answer differs.

00:46:20.240 --> 00:46:22.053
AUDIENCE: OK, yeah,
for someone who maybe

00:46:22.053 --> 00:46:23.220
doesn't have a lot of money.

00:46:23.220 --> 00:46:24.595
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Somebody who

00:46:24.595 --> 00:46:26.830
doesn't have a lot of
money, you basically

00:46:26.830 --> 00:46:28.630
belong to an organization.

00:46:28.630 --> 00:46:31.360
You care about gun rights, you
belong to the National Rifle

00:46:31.360 --> 00:46:32.530
Association.

00:46:32.530 --> 00:46:38.170
You care about
abortion, you contribute

00:46:38.170 --> 00:46:42.430
to the National Abortion Rights
Act, whatever the thing is,

00:46:42.430 --> 00:46:44.560
or Planned Parenthood.

00:46:44.560 --> 00:46:48.040
You can contribute
to organizations

00:46:48.040 --> 00:46:51.100
or you can contribute
to candidates.

00:46:51.100 --> 00:46:55.750
If you're Warren Buffett, you
can set up a political action

00:46:55.750 --> 00:46:57.970
committee--

00:46:57.970 --> 00:47:01.750
he doesn't do this-- put a
few tens of millions of in it,

00:47:01.750 --> 00:47:04.510
look around the country
for candidates you like,

00:47:04.510 --> 00:47:06.197
and spend for them.

00:47:06.197 --> 00:47:07.280
You can't give it to them.

00:47:07.280 --> 00:47:08.920
You can spend for them.

00:47:08.920 --> 00:47:10.750
You can hire people
to write attack ads

00:47:10.750 --> 00:47:15.300
against their opponents and put
a lot of money in television,

00:47:15.300 --> 00:47:17.100
or you can also find
interest groups.

00:47:19.690 --> 00:47:22.030
AUDIENCE: My question is
if I care a lot about--

00:47:22.030 --> 00:47:25.900
I have a [INAUDIBLE] because
I buy electricity [INAUDIBLE],,

00:47:25.900 --> 00:47:29.200
but maybe I really care
about guns or something.

00:47:29.200 --> 00:47:32.710
So what would the
ideal system be

00:47:32.710 --> 00:47:35.680
in which I can have interest
in all these different groups,

00:47:35.680 --> 00:47:40.150
but the ones that I care about
more get more of my support.

00:47:40.150 --> 00:47:42.520
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Well,
if there are organizations--

00:47:42.520 --> 00:47:44.110
I mean, the National
Rifle Association

00:47:44.110 --> 00:47:45.525
is politically active.

00:47:45.525 --> 00:47:46.900
So if you care
about guns, that's

00:47:46.900 --> 00:47:48.348
a place you can send money.

00:47:48.348 --> 00:47:49.390
They'll spend it for you.

00:47:51.930 --> 00:47:54.820
If you're old you, the
American Association of Retired

00:47:54.820 --> 00:47:55.320
Persons--

00:47:55.320 --> 00:47:57.243
I mean, there are
plenty of pockets.

00:47:57.243 --> 00:47:59.160
AUDIENCE: The things
that I care a lot about I

00:47:59.160 --> 00:48:03.930
can give more money
to than other things.

00:48:03.930 --> 00:48:04.770
So that works--

00:48:04.770 --> 00:48:05.220
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:48:05.220 --> 00:48:05.610
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Sort of.

00:48:05.610 --> 00:48:07.068
AUDIENCE: --money
But then my voice

00:48:07.068 --> 00:48:09.383
is smaller because I
have less money in total.

00:48:09.383 --> 00:48:11.550
So someone who maybe doesn't
care as much about this

00:48:11.550 --> 00:48:14.920
can give a little money, too,
but still larger than my voice.

00:48:14.920 --> 00:48:18.780
So money seems like the most
efficient system that I can

00:48:18.780 --> 00:48:22.020
think of that allows people to
contribute to things they care

00:48:22.020 --> 00:48:24.420
about a lot, and have
their voices heard there,

00:48:24.420 --> 00:48:26.370
whereas things they
don't care about,

00:48:26.370 --> 00:48:27.825
but they're part
of, they don't--

00:48:27.825 --> 00:48:29.850
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
The issue that disturbs

00:48:29.850 --> 00:48:31.925
people is sort of twofold.

00:48:31.925 --> 00:48:33.300
One of the things
that's happened

00:48:33.300 --> 00:48:37.140
in this country over
the last 30 years,

00:48:37.140 --> 00:48:39.090
maybe goes back
a little farther,

00:48:39.090 --> 00:48:43.530
is increasing inequality
of income and wealth.

00:48:43.530 --> 00:48:48.120
I think it's very hard to
point a policy finger at what's

00:48:48.120 --> 00:48:50.190
done that, and it's
very complicated

00:48:50.190 --> 00:48:52.350
to figure out what's
done it, but it has

00:48:52.350 --> 00:48:54.580
happened one way or another.

00:48:54.580 --> 00:48:56.760
And so the thing
that upsets people

00:48:56.760 --> 00:49:02.450
is the difference in the
size of Warren Buffett's

00:49:02.450 --> 00:49:04.910
voice and your voice.

00:49:04.910 --> 00:49:07.340
If it's one person,
one vote, we don't all

00:49:07.340 --> 00:49:11.750
have equal impact on the
process with contributions.

00:49:11.750 --> 00:49:17.780
In fact, they differ by several
multiple orders of magnitude.

00:49:17.780 --> 00:49:18.830
That's the upset.

00:49:18.830 --> 00:49:22.310
I have no problem with-- and
the campaign finance laws

00:49:22.310 --> 00:49:24.410
were supposed to deal with that.

00:49:24.410 --> 00:49:26.600
The idea was A,
corporations can't

00:49:26.600 --> 00:49:30.830
make political
contributions, and B,

00:49:30.830 --> 00:49:33.530
there's a limit on how much
an individual can spend.

00:49:33.530 --> 00:49:36.110
That was intended
to equalize voice.

00:49:36.110 --> 00:49:38.330
You can still give to
various organizations

00:49:38.330 --> 00:49:43.220
as much as you want, but in
terms of the electoral process,

00:49:43.220 --> 00:49:44.850
there were limits.

00:49:44.850 --> 00:49:48.120
Those laws are no
longer relevant because

00:49:48.120 --> 00:49:49.568
of Citizens United.

00:49:49.568 --> 00:49:50.610
I mean, that's the issue.

00:49:50.610 --> 00:49:54.720
I mean, I've got no problem
with people spending money.

00:49:54.720 --> 00:50:00.000
I'm not profoundly upset
at the current system,

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:04.500
but the huge difference
in the ability of somebody

00:50:04.500 --> 00:50:07.620
like this casino owner
who gave $15 million

00:50:07.620 --> 00:50:10.950
to the Newt Gingrich campaign--

00:50:10.950 --> 00:50:14.830
that's one guy carrying
a presidential campaign.

00:50:14.830 --> 00:50:15.330
Wow.

00:50:18.600 --> 00:50:23.370
That no longer sounds
like Athenian democracy.

00:50:23.370 --> 00:50:24.334
Yeah.

00:50:24.334 --> 00:50:26.890
AUDIENCE: Two points-- one,
couldn't a voucher system

00:50:26.890 --> 00:50:28.260
solve this problem?

00:50:28.260 --> 00:50:31.208
Like something proposed
by Lawrence Lessig.

00:50:31.208 --> 00:50:33.750
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Say what
you mean by a "voucher system."

00:50:33.750 --> 00:50:35.333
AUDIENCE: So what
Lawrence Lessig says

00:50:35.333 --> 00:50:39.390
is that each individual
has $50 tax credit,

00:50:39.390 --> 00:50:41.850
and that money goes towards
funding a candidate.

00:50:41.850 --> 00:50:43.430
And there's no other outside--

00:50:43.430 --> 00:50:43.890
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:50:43.890 --> 00:50:46.390
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Yeah, it's
the "no other outside money"

00:50:46.390 --> 00:50:48.810
that violates the
Constitution, almost certainly.

00:50:48.810 --> 00:50:52.253
So let me move
forward a little bit.

00:50:52.253 --> 00:50:53.670
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
second part.

00:50:53.670 --> 00:50:54.530
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Yeah, please.

00:50:54.530 --> 00:50:55.947
AUDIENCE: Wouldn't
pure capitalism

00:50:55.947 --> 00:50:58.560
solve this problem
because the governments

00:50:58.560 --> 00:50:59.737
aren't involved then.

00:50:59.737 --> 00:51:02.070
And if you're buying milk,
it's the consumer [INAUDIBLE]

00:51:02.070 --> 00:51:03.330
supply.

00:51:03.330 --> 00:51:04.913
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE:
Oh, you're saying

00:51:04.913 --> 00:51:07.300
that you should limit
the scope of government

00:51:07.300 --> 00:51:09.120
so you can limit the
mischief it can do.

00:51:09.120 --> 00:51:11.357
AUDIENCE: In theory.

00:51:11.357 --> 00:51:12.440
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: Sure.

00:51:12.440 --> 00:51:14.780
Why are we trying to
raise the price of milk,

00:51:14.780 --> 00:51:15.920
for heaven's sakes?

00:51:15.920 --> 00:51:18.570
Because dairy farmers
are a very effective

00:51:18.570 --> 00:51:19.820
organized group and have been.

00:51:19.820 --> 00:51:21.278
Why do we raise
the price of sugar?

00:51:21.278 --> 00:51:25.790
Because if we didn't have
barriers to trade in sugar,

00:51:25.790 --> 00:51:27.920
we would undoubtedly
buy Cuban sugar,

00:51:27.920 --> 00:51:30.200
and we don't wish
to buy Cuban sugar.

00:51:30.200 --> 00:51:34.670
Oh, and by the way,
they're sugar producers.

00:51:34.670 --> 00:51:40.640
Anyway, lobbying-- let me
urge you read the short piece

00:51:40.640 --> 00:51:42.710
by [? Kline ?] and
[? Steller. ?] It's not

00:51:42.710 --> 00:51:45.560
on the syllabus because
it came out this spring.

00:51:45.560 --> 00:51:48.980
It's a very nice description
consistent with all

00:51:48.980 --> 00:51:54.130
my experience of
how lobbying works.

00:51:54.130 --> 00:51:56.770
Effective lobbyists don't
walk in with bags of money

00:51:56.770 --> 00:51:57.940
to buy votes.

00:51:57.940 --> 00:52:01.360
Effective lobbyists
make friends.

00:52:01.360 --> 00:52:04.210
They get in to talk.

00:52:04.210 --> 00:52:07.300
They provide information.

00:52:07.300 --> 00:52:11.140
The information is, of course,
slanted, but it's your friend.

00:52:11.140 --> 00:52:13.060
It's a very
interesting description

00:52:13.060 --> 00:52:15.820
of what the guy calls
a "gift economy," where

00:52:15.820 --> 00:52:18.790
basically you're doing favors.

00:52:18.790 --> 00:52:20.800
You have a complicated
piece of legislation.

00:52:20.800 --> 00:52:24.730
I'll discuss it with you when
we play golf next Saturday.

00:52:24.730 --> 00:52:25.960
We're good friends.

00:52:25.960 --> 00:52:27.707
How did I get hired
as a lobbyist?

00:52:27.707 --> 00:52:29.290
Because I'm friends
with these people.

00:52:29.290 --> 00:52:30.880
That's how I got
hired as a lobbyist,

00:52:30.880 --> 00:52:34.990
so they'll play golf with me,
so I can tell them this stuff.

00:52:34.990 --> 00:52:37.390
Yeah, maybe I give
them some tickets,

00:52:37.390 --> 00:52:39.700
but I'm not going to buy
their votes with money

00:52:39.700 --> 00:52:41.210
for a whole set of reasons.

00:52:41.210 --> 00:52:44.200
First of all, you go to jail
for that if you're caught.

00:52:44.200 --> 00:52:47.830
And second of all,
most people in Congress

00:52:47.830 --> 00:52:50.320
don't think of
themselves as crooks.

00:52:50.320 --> 00:52:54.310
They think of themselves as
trying to do the right thing.

00:52:54.310 --> 00:52:59.260
So the process of lobbying
is very, very nicely

00:52:59.260 --> 00:53:01.300
described in that article.

00:53:01.300 --> 00:53:02.860
And again, it's
because I've seen it,

00:53:02.860 --> 00:53:04.610
it's consistent with
everything I've seen.

00:53:07.960 --> 00:53:11.170
You become an effective lobby
not because you have more money

00:53:11.170 --> 00:53:13.600
to swing around, but
because you can hire

00:53:13.600 --> 00:53:15.520
people who have connections.

00:53:15.520 --> 00:53:20.560
You can get information
prepared that's useful,

00:53:20.560 --> 00:53:24.040
and you have the ability to
affect campaign contributions.

00:53:24.040 --> 00:53:25.360
That does matter.

00:53:25.360 --> 00:53:28.130
But it's a very
different process.

00:53:28.130 --> 00:53:31.780
It's a process of influence,
not a process of bribery.

00:53:31.780 --> 00:53:32.950
So I urge you to read that.

00:53:32.950 --> 00:53:34.060
It's short.

00:53:34.060 --> 00:53:41.230
So quickly, [? Loewy ?] makes
the point interest group

00:53:41.230 --> 00:53:44.320
competition is one
kind of politics.

00:53:44.320 --> 00:53:47.260
It really is inside baseball.

00:53:47.260 --> 00:53:52.540
But if you look at various
kinds of political action

00:53:52.540 --> 00:53:55.210
and various kinds of
governmental action,

00:53:55.210 --> 00:53:56.750
it doesn't all fit.

00:53:56.750 --> 00:53:59.180
This is a set of possibilities.

00:53:59.180 --> 00:54:01.690
This is impact on
the Federal Reserve.

00:54:01.690 --> 00:54:04.000
Well, is that interest groups?

00:54:04.000 --> 00:54:08.110
Antitrust policy-- is
that interest groups?

00:54:08.110 --> 00:54:11.500
Reapportionment-- well,
that's more complicated.

00:54:11.500 --> 00:54:17.830
Tariffs-- tariff policy
is winners and losers.

00:54:17.830 --> 00:54:23.320
Milk price supports is
