Now, this is the piece by Whitt.

00:54:48.310 --> 00:54:53.470
And Whitt is a Marxist, so Whitt
is very big on class dialectic.

00:54:53.470 --> 00:54:56.270
And if you can make sense out
of that, you're one up on me.

00:54:56.270 --> 00:55:01.210
But I think the middle column,
the split between the two

00:55:01.210 --> 00:55:02.590
columns is interesting.

00:55:02.590 --> 00:55:05.200
If you think about
politics in China

00:55:05.200 --> 00:55:07.450
or if you think about
traditional politics

00:55:07.450 --> 00:55:09.160
in Latin American
countries, where

00:55:09.160 --> 00:55:11.260
they would talk
about the oligarchy,

00:55:11.260 --> 00:55:15.850
you would think about
this middle column.

00:55:15.850 --> 00:55:20.330
You would think about
politics by the elite.

00:55:20.330 --> 00:55:26.870
Read descriptions of
politics in Haiti, et cetera.

00:55:26.870 --> 00:55:29.630
There are a number of situations
in which it makes sense

00:55:29.630 --> 00:55:31.250
to think about.

00:55:31.250 --> 00:55:35.810
And if you read
older descriptions

00:55:35.810 --> 00:55:39.680
in Boston of the
vault, which is what

00:55:39.680 --> 00:55:41.840
all the business
and civic leaders

00:55:41.840 --> 00:55:45.770
would get together in the
vault of the Bank of Boston,

00:55:45.770 --> 00:55:50.523
you sort of have a politics that
doesn't look so much like this.

00:55:50.523 --> 00:55:52.190
This is really a
[? Loewy ?] description

00:55:52.190 --> 00:55:54.950
over here, a very nice
[? Loewy ?] description

00:55:54.950 --> 00:55:56.870
of how it ought to work.

00:55:56.870 --> 00:56:01.590
But in fact, there are
situations in which in essence,

00:56:01.590 --> 00:56:03.500
there is a relatively
small elite that

00:56:03.500 --> 00:56:04.700
controls the government.

00:56:04.700 --> 00:56:07.250
They may control the
government for exploitation.

00:56:07.250 --> 00:56:09.750
They may control the
government for who knows what,

00:56:09.750 --> 00:56:11.070
but it's a club.

00:56:11.070 --> 00:56:13.580
It's a small club.

00:56:13.580 --> 00:56:15.920
And there are situations
that look like that.

00:56:15.920 --> 00:56:19.400
The US doesn't look like that
so much because our politics are

00:56:19.400 --> 00:56:20.810
less well organized.

00:56:20.810 --> 00:56:23.300
Latin countries always
used to look like that.

00:56:23.300 --> 00:56:25.280
They're less so now.

00:56:25.280 --> 00:56:31.400
But again, listen to
[? Evita ?] and hear

00:56:31.400 --> 00:56:34.610
them talk about the oligarchy.

00:56:34.610 --> 00:56:36.050
So there are a
number of settings

00:56:36.050 --> 00:56:38.660
in which it makes sense to
think about the politics

00:56:38.660 --> 00:56:43.130
as elite control, not
interest group competition.

00:56:43.130 --> 00:56:45.350
You might think about that.

00:56:45.350 --> 00:56:49.670
There are also situations
that don't fit any of these,

00:56:49.670 --> 00:56:53.630
and I'll talk about
some of those.

00:56:53.630 --> 00:56:57.170
What I want to do
now is begin the lead

00:56:57.170 --> 00:57:04.070
into the discussion of
clean air as an example

00:57:04.070 --> 00:57:07.010
where a number of these and
some other things surface.

00:57:07.010 --> 00:57:09.090
So I realize that
to do that case,

00:57:09.090 --> 00:57:11.780
you have to have a little
background on the structure

00:57:11.780 --> 00:57:13.460
of federal regulation.

00:57:13.460 --> 00:57:14.660
And let me do that now.

00:57:14.660 --> 00:57:17.930
Please try to stay awake.

00:57:17.930 --> 00:57:26.450
The way the US system works,
typically, is laws are vague.

00:57:26.450 --> 00:57:29.480
Laws say things like,
"EPA must set a standard

00:57:29.480 --> 00:57:34.700
to protect human health," or
"the public utility commission

00:57:34.700 --> 00:57:37.580
shall ensure that electricity
prices are just, reasonable,

00:57:37.580 --> 00:57:40.670
and not unduly discriminatory."

00:57:40.670 --> 00:57:44.870
Very commonly, this is a
very standard-- sometimes

00:57:44.870 --> 00:57:47.043
that's handed to a
cabinet department--

00:57:47.043 --> 00:57:49.460
the Department of Agriculture,
the Department of Interior,

00:57:49.460 --> 00:57:50.030
whatever.

00:57:50.030 --> 00:57:51.860
Sometimes, it's
handed to an agency.

00:57:51.860 --> 00:57:56.000
We're talking here
mostly about agencies.

00:57:56.000 --> 00:57:59.228
They come in two forms--

00:57:59.228 --> 00:58:00.770
they're either
independent or they're

00:58:00.770 --> 00:58:03.033
part of the executive branch.

00:58:03.033 --> 00:58:04.700
If they're part of
the executive branch,

00:58:04.700 --> 00:58:07.310
like EPA, the President
appoints the head.

00:58:07.310 --> 00:58:09.950
The President can fire the head.

00:58:09.950 --> 00:58:12.650
If they're independent,
the President

00:58:12.650 --> 00:58:15.800
will be able to appoint the
head but not remove them,

00:58:15.800 --> 00:58:18.200
except to show cause.

00:58:18.200 --> 00:58:20.840
You can fire the head of EPA
because he or she ticked you

00:58:20.840 --> 00:58:22.040
off.

00:58:22.040 --> 00:58:25.130
To fire the head of FERC,
you have to show cause.

00:58:25.130 --> 00:58:27.450
That can be challenged
in court, and so forth.

00:58:27.450 --> 00:58:29.900
So they are independent.

00:58:29.900 --> 00:58:33.920
They were invented around in
the teens of the last century.

00:58:33.920 --> 00:58:35.810
The idea was to
make them-- well,

00:58:35.810 --> 00:58:37.400
there were some
earlier examples,

00:58:37.400 --> 00:58:40.280
but it was really pushed then.

00:58:40.280 --> 00:58:41.870
The idea was these
will be expert

00:58:41.870 --> 00:58:43.340
bodies immune to politics.

00:58:43.340 --> 00:58:46.520
The Federal Trade Commission
is one such like that it.

00:58:46.520 --> 00:58:48.980
It has its own building.

00:58:48.980 --> 00:58:51.080
It gets its money from Congress.

00:58:51.080 --> 00:58:53.720
It doesn't report
to the President.

00:58:53.720 --> 00:58:56.480
The President appoints people
with the consent of Congress,

00:58:56.480 --> 00:58:58.130
can't fire them.

00:58:58.130 --> 00:59:00.890
Often, they have
to be bipartisan--

00:59:00.890 --> 00:59:03.500
two Republicans, two
Democrats, something like that.

00:59:06.037 --> 00:59:06.995
They could be captured.

00:59:12.740 --> 00:59:15.740
They could be captured by
the regulated interests.

00:59:15.740 --> 00:59:17.870
It's argued that FERC is
captured by the utilities.

00:59:17.870 --> 00:59:20.760
I don't think that's true,
but you can make the case.

00:59:20.760 --> 00:59:23.030
And the idea of
putting EPA, which

00:59:23.030 --> 00:59:25.010
is a later creation,
in the executive branch

00:59:25.010 --> 00:59:28.430
was to make it responsive to
politics, make it responsible.

00:59:31.940 --> 00:59:35.270
It affects the
kind of oversight.

00:59:35.270 --> 00:59:39.410
Rules passed by EPA,
rules proposed by EPA,

00:59:39.410 --> 00:59:43.190
are reviewed by the Office
of Information and Regulatory

00:59:43.190 --> 00:59:46.100
Analysis in the Office
of Management and Budget.

00:59:46.100 --> 00:59:48.170
They can be called
in on the carpet.

00:59:48.170 --> 00:59:50.000
They can be fired.

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:51.530
All kinds of things
could happen.

00:59:51.530 --> 00:59:54.200
The Federal Communications
Commission, or the FERC,

00:59:54.200 --> 00:59:55.910
or state public
utility commissions,

00:59:55.910 --> 00:59:59.378
are not reviewed in that
fashion by the President,

00:59:59.378 --> 01:00:01.170
or the President's
people, or the governor,

01:00:01.170 --> 01:00:03.060
or the governor's people.

01:00:03.060 --> 01:00:08.220
But all decisions by
regulatory agencies

01:00:08.220 --> 01:00:11.100
can be reviewed in the courts.

01:00:11.100 --> 01:00:13.260
So here's the architecture.

01:00:13.260 --> 01:00:16.080
The law says it's got to
be just and reasonable.

01:00:16.080 --> 01:00:20.340
It's got to protect,
blah, blah, blah.

01:00:20.340 --> 01:00:22.980
In some cases, the
President or the governor

01:00:22.980 --> 01:00:25.620
can review it,
more commonly not.

01:00:25.620 --> 01:00:29.640
It gets reviewed by the courts
under the Administrative

01:00:29.640 --> 01:00:34.170
Procedures Act of 1946,
or related state acts.

01:00:34.170 --> 01:00:38.760
The court can reject
an action that's

01:00:38.760 --> 01:00:41.040
arbitrary and capricious,
an abuse of discretion,

01:00:41.040 --> 01:00:43.420
or not otherwise in
accordance with the law.

01:00:43.420 --> 01:00:47.070
So the law says you have
to protect human health.

01:00:47.070 --> 01:00:50.040
The agency has no
evidence on health.

01:00:50.040 --> 01:00:52.620
The court will say, that's
arbitrary and capricious,

01:00:52.620 --> 01:00:54.390
and throw it out.

01:00:54.390 --> 01:00:59.770
Or you didn't take into
account public comment.

01:00:59.770 --> 01:01:04.080
So here is where organized
interest groups matter.

01:01:04.080 --> 01:01:06.180
So the agency is going
to make a decision.

01:01:06.180 --> 01:01:08.445
It has to take
comments, usually.

01:01:11.360 --> 01:01:17.300
And the American Public
Power Association

01:01:17.300 --> 01:01:20.210
will file comments
on everything. e

01:01:20.210 --> 01:01:21.685
which is this
electricity consumers

01:01:21.685 --> 01:01:23.810
organization, will file
comments on everything that

01:01:23.810 --> 01:01:25.310
has to do with electricity.

01:01:25.310 --> 01:01:27.810
You and I won't.

01:01:27.810 --> 01:01:32.050
As will every utility in
the land, and who knows,

01:01:32.050 --> 01:01:33.300
General Electric.

01:01:33.300 --> 01:01:36.390
Organized interest groups
will file comments.

01:01:36.390 --> 01:01:39.480
And the courts
will reject a rule

01:01:39.480 --> 01:01:43.450
that doesn't take adequate
account of public comment.

01:01:43.450 --> 01:01:49.500
So if somebody proves that a
chemical is cancer causing,

01:01:49.500 --> 01:01:54.180
and EPA says, no,
it'll be thrown out.

01:01:54.180 --> 01:01:57.330
You've got to consider
the evidence that's

01:01:57.330 --> 01:02:00.060
submitted in the process.

01:02:00.060 --> 01:02:02.580
That's the regulatory process,
particularly as it relates

01:02:02.580 --> 01:02:06.050
to environmental regulation--

01:02:06.050 --> 01:02:10.520
fairly vague laws, not
always, not on all terms,

01:02:10.520 --> 01:02:13.040
but usually fairly
vague, hands it off,

01:02:13.040 --> 01:02:15.290
delegates to the agency.

01:02:15.290 --> 01:02:20.300
Sometimes, in the case of EPA,
reviewed by the White House,

01:02:20.300 --> 01:02:21.290
sometimes not.

01:02:21.290 --> 01:02:25.570
Always reviewable by
the courts, always

01:02:25.570 --> 01:02:27.640
a requirement to take
into account comments.

01:02:32.860 --> 01:02:35.410
You might ask, who would
work in a regulatory agency?

01:02:35.410 --> 01:02:37.480
And we'll talk
about that briefly.

01:02:37.480 --> 01:02:42.460
But is that process
reasonably straightforward?

01:02:42.460 --> 01:02:43.106
Yeah.

01:02:43.106 --> 01:02:44.255
AUDIENCE: Would it
take into account

01:02:44.255 --> 01:02:45.338
who's making the comments?

01:02:49.780 --> 01:02:50.780
RICHARD SCHMALENSEE: No.

01:02:50.780 --> 01:02:54.030
You take into account
the evidence provided.

01:02:54.030 --> 01:02:57.470
So if the large
electricity consumers, say,

01:02:57.470 --> 01:03:00.200
we think that rates
too high, well, there's

01:03:00.200 --> 01:03:02.210
nothing to take into account.

01:03:02.210 --> 01:03:09.110
If they say, here's a study that
shows that 10% of our members

01:03:09.110 --> 01:03:12.050
will be driven bankrupt
by these prices,

01:03:12.050 --> 01:03:18.540
and the study is not junk,
they have to consider that.

01:03:18.540 --> 01:03:22.340
So they're not obliged, in
fact, they're almost obliged

01:03:22.340 --> 01:03:25.580
not to take into
account the source,

01:03:25.580 --> 01:03:29.810
but to focus on the content,
which is sort of sensible.

01:03:29.810 --> 01:03:30.890
Yeah.

01:03:30.890 --> 01:03:33.850
Anything else?

01:03:33.850 --> 01:03:37.850
Yeah, you actually
have to make arguments.

01:03:37.850 --> 01:03:42.892
OK, so we've been talking
about interest group politics.

01:03:42.892 --> 01:03:44.100
We're talking about factions.

01:03:48.750 --> 01:03:51.760
How did that act get passed?

01:03:51.760 --> 01:03:54.477
Was that interest
group competition?

01:03:54.477 --> 01:03:56.060
Did interest group
competition give us

01:03:56.060 --> 01:04:00.620
the Clean Air Act of 1970?

01:04:00.620 --> 01:04:01.970
